data.content:
Your assertions work but produce poor failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions that tell you *what* went wrong:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // no built-in equivalent; IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users); // or:
    // var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `IsNotEmpty(list)` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `HasCount(3, list)` | Shows "Expected 3, got 5" |
| `IsTrue(x != null)` | `IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent |
| `Single()` + null check | `ContainsSingle()` | Better failure message |

The general rule: **avoid `Assert.IsTrue` when a specialized assertion exists** — you get descriptive failure messages instead of just "expected True, got False".
